China's Investment Dependence
Beijing — China's economy unexpectedly slowed in the second quarter of this year.
Equally unexpected is that most of the data released since July have indicated that China's growth has stabilized.
It is no surprise that the markets have simultaneously breathed a sigh of relief.
But should investors remain on edge?
The most serious problem currently facing Chinese authorities is overcapacity.
For example, China's annual crude steel production capacity is 10 billion tons, but total output in 2012 was only 7.2 billion tons — a capacity utilization rate of 72%.
More notably, the profit margin of the steel industry in 2012 was only 0.04%.
In fact, the profit from producing one ton of steel could only buy one lollipop.
So far this year, the average profit margin of China's top 500 companies is 4.34%, down 33 basis points from 2012.
Some say today's overcapacity stems from excessive investment in the past.
Others believe overcapacity is due to insufficient effective demand.
The government's view seems to be a compromise between the two.
On one hand, the authorities are asking thousands of companies to cut production capacity.
On the other hand, the government has introduced some "mini stimulus" measures, such as exempting "micro enterprises" from business taxes and sales taxes, and requiring banks to increase lending to export-oriented companies.
The official line of the authorities is that China's growth model needs to reduce investment and increase consumption.
But not all Chinese economists agree with this.
They argue that the stock of capital is a key factor in growth, and China's per capita capital stock is still relatively low compared to developed countries, which means there is still a large scope for future investment.
Indeed, capital accumulation is a major driver of economic growth, and catching up with the income levels of developed countries requires China to increase its capital stock in the long term.
But what matters is not the size of the capital stock, or even the level of investment; what matters is the growth rate of investment, which has been much higher than the GDP growth rate for decades.
According to official statistics, China's investment rate has approached 50% of its GDP.
Due to absorption constraints, capital efficiency steadily declines as the scale of capital increases.
When the environmental damage caused by the rapidly growing investment is taken into account, China's capital efficiency would be even lower.
The role of human capital and technological progress in economic growth is no less significant than that of physical capital and labor.
If the tilt of resource allocation toward physical capital comes at the expense of human capital accumulation — which is an indispensable condition for adequate consumption — economic growth is more likely to slow down rather than accelerate.
Therefore, China should reduce the growth rate of investment and increase the growth rate of consumption, stabilizing the investment rate at a more sustainable level.
Of course, it is not entirely wrong to say that China's overcapacity reflects insufficient effective demand.
But where does effective demand come from?
In this regard, China's steel industry again provides a good example.
Although China has no comparative advantage in steel production, it still built about one thousand steel plants, accounting for half of the world's total output.
As early as 2004, the Chinese government attempted to cool down excessive investment; however, due to the strong demand brought about by infrastructure investment and real estate development, output continued to grow rapidly, increasing from 300 million tons that year to 1 billion tons in 2012.
China's investment can generally be divided into three categories: manufacturing, infrastructure, and real estate.
At the peak of the global financial crisis in late 2008 and 2009, infrastructure investment driven by economic stimulus maintained output growth.
In 2010, real estate development investment replaced infrastructure investment as the main driver of growth.
Today, infrastructure and real estate are both important drivers of China's growth.
China indeed needs more infrastructure investment — particularly in electricity and hydropower, transportation, and communication.
However, the pace of investment must fully take into account financial constraints.
More importantly, China can and should invest more in social infrastructure such as schools, hospitals, and nursing homes.
But real estate investment is a different matter.
It is difficult to assess the severity of China's real estate bubble and the timing of its potential collapse.
But one thing is certain: China has invested too much in real estate development.
China's per capita income is less than $6,000, yet its homeownership rate is as high as about 90%, while in the United States it is less than 70%.
The per capita housing area is 32.9 square meters, while the median household housing area in Hong Kong has just reached 48 square meters.
China has 696 five-star hotels, with another 500 under construction.
Five of the ten tallest buildings under construction are located in China.
In my view, this can only be described as madness.
China's economy is being held hostage by real estate investment.
On one hand, China should not address overcapacity by maintaining a high growth rate of real estate investment.
Social housing project investments are welcome, but the current level of real estate investment, which accounts for as high as 10-13% of GDP, is already too high.
On the other hand, if real estate investment growth declines, overcapacity cannot be eliminated.
This dilemma highlights the structural adjustment challenges faced by China — and should also make investors cautious.
All in all, there are two points worth being cautious about.
First, unlike other types of investment, real estate investment does not increase the stock of productive capital.
Houses and high-priced durable consumer goods are fundamentally no different.
Second, in China's statistical data, the growth rate of total fixed asset investment is significantly higher than the growth rate of total capital formation.
This suggests that the growth rate of fixed investment may overstate the speed of capital stock accumulation.
Therefore, although the Chinese government should firmly reduce its reliance on investment for economic growth, the actions must be very cautious.
